<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-04-07T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-04-07T20:00:00-05:00" n="738" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d738">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861a.01/228: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Warren</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-04-08T10:00:00+09:00"><hi rend="italic">April 8,
                                        1922—10 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 8—8:50
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>59. Following from Vladivostok dated April 5, 11 a.m.</p>
                        <p>“There are unofficial reports that battle at Spassk was on larger scale
                            than the Japanese have indicated and that losses on both sides were
                            heavy. Monday and Tuesday the Japanese sent 99 troop cars, that is,
                            about 2,500 men, from Nikolsk to Spassk. Today they are sending 64 troop
                            cars from Vladivostok to Nikolsk.[”]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Warren</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
